Genesis to Revelation is folkpop and very Moody Blues inspired
Trespass and Nursery Cryme continue this folk sound but a lot more proggy and I think more somber. Really cool British storytelling
Foxtrot and Selling England by the Pound are equally proggy but also very theatrical, incorporating elements of genres like music hall. That description may sound similar to Lamb Lies Down, but they focus on British storytelling like their earlier albums and the folk sound is still there

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114109205
From Genesis to Revelation is Moody Blues-inspired folkpop
Trespass and Nursery Cryme are where they get more proggy but still within the folk realm. A lot more somber in my opinion. Wonderful storytelling. Their most underrated stuff
Foxtrot and Selling England By The Pound is still similar to their other stuff but a lot more theatric (using elements of music hall for example), their classical music inspiration being a lot more upfront as well, and more rock-oriented (psychedelic rock and of course progressive rock), but still within their British folk roots as far as overall sound and storytelling/lyricism goes. This is the fan favorite era.

>>114120423
Yeah, Japan's a nation of avant-prog and brutal prog and prog metal.
While they do have traditional progressive rock, it's usually very derivative, there's not a lot of truly notable Japanese traditional prog groups. Experimental/avant/brutal prog stuff is where Jap prog really shines but it can come off as overly indulgent and unlistenable.

Even when Tatsuya Yoshida formed Koenji Hyakkei with the intention of being less inaccessible compared to Ruins, more in line with Magma and wearing its influences from bands like Gentle Giant and Genesis on its sleeves, it's still way too much for a lot of Western prog fans.

I've read arts critics basically describe punk as the avant-garde phase of rock music.

The idea is basically this: every art movement goes through three stages: an early formative phase, a renaissance phase with tons of room for innovation, and then a post-modern, avant-garde phase where people pick apart and reorganize the form to create something new. By this standard, the early phase is early rock music in the 50s and early 60s. The renaissance phase is the late 60s and early 70s, with "classic rock" bands like Led Zeppelin, The Who, and The Jimi Hendrix Experience. Then things slowed down, it was harder to do new things in the rock format, so the punk/alternative movement ripped apart conventions and reorganized the whole thing.

Rock has a standard structure, with the intro, chorus, bridge, chorus, whatever, 3 minutes. Some punk bands went back to that energetic early format, like some of The Clash's stuff. But there were also really ambitious, noisy art bands dispelling of that, like Richard Hell, Suicide, Pere Ubu, and the no wave bands. Of course, the krautrock bands had gone a lot further a few years earlier, but that's neither here nor there.

The hardcore bands for the most part weren't artsy, but they threw away the rock format even more than most punk bands. It was just straight to a noisy rant. A lot of early hardcore is actually surprisingly catchy, but it was a rejection of a lot of rock standards. The interesting thing is that over time hardcore developed its own structure, separate from conventional rock, with things like breakdowns, chant-alongs, etc.

>>114169756
it seems to me that rock music was already so diversified in the late sixties (pop rock, psychedelia, blues rock, hard rock) that your theory, while interesting, doesn't fit the facts. Why is psychedelia pat of the "classic era" and not the first sign of avant-garde? And what about Frank Zappa and Capt Beefheart?

I see rock music as a movement fragmented into genres and subgenres that evolve continuously: the Ramones invented punk in 1976 influenced by different artists from the 60s pop to the early 70s hard rock, but more than a purely musical phenomenon I see punk as a cultural revolution, that is, the anger and nihilism of the post-60s generation. New York's new wave soon incorporated elements of punk in a more intellectual and sophisticated style. Hardcore punk is, as >>114169725 says, a reactionary genre that protests the new wave by stretching to the extreme the concepts of original punk.

Overall I would agree that the birth of punk has been one of the break points of rock music, and that was bc it was not just the next step in rock evolution but the response to the need of a young, angry, post-60s audience, understood by those new artists.

>>114148670
there's not really a right or wrong way to music. if people like the song, you did it the right way. there's lots of "rules" for producing, but rules are made to be bent and sometimes broken entirely. me personally, i only use like 3 fx on my master fx chain. less is more imo.

i'd say get really good at getting great sound with 3 basic plugins. EQ, Compression, and Reverb. those are like salt pepper and garlic. i don't think there's an album made since 1950 that DIDN'T use those fx. They're essential. practice getting good sounds from just those three, the branch out. that's just my opinion.

>>114148670

here is your masterclass:

1. never put anything on master, ever, leave that for... mastering.
2. high pass literally everything, but do so subtly; too much will remove the character of the sound.
3. add subtle saturation/distortion to all of your busses. yes, really, everything. subtle distortion generates upper harmonics, which means you can get away with carving off more low end to make room in the mix without losing the sound of the track. (make sure you apply distortion BEFORE eq'ing however)
4. use busses/groups to group and effect similar tracks.
5. use LCR mixing; double (or triple) tracking takes and panning them hard R/L (and center if you're triple tracking) is a really powerful technique that generates good stereo image; be careful of phase though, and monitor in mono to make sure compatibility is good.
6. use compression; use it basically everywhere. learning how to dial in a compressor is an art, and should be done in a subtle way.
7. use parallel processing. this ties in with the last point. every bus should have a rack of effects in parallel (in ableton, this is called an "Audio Effect Rack"). in general, each rack should have 1. a clean signal 2. a compressed signal, and 3. a 100% wet reverb signal. you can of course add other effects. generally speaking, my busses typically look like: distortion -> EQ -> parallel processing rack described above.
8. use targeted bell filters in your EQ to bring out instruments in your mix; make sure different part don't have the same frequency ranges accentuated however.

digesting and internalizing this will get you a long, long way. some people may disagree with certain parts of this, but this is the stuff i wish i knew a very long time ago.

I dislike grunge, but I'd say 1988 to 1991 was probably the last era in which rock was actually exciting and had vitality, talent, and diversity. So many different fucking things were being done at the same time, from faggoty alt rock to extreme metal for cavemen (and everything in between and beyond) that it'd literally be impossible to cover the genres of the time without making some autist spreadsheet.

The 80s hard rock and thrash bands were at their most popular in 1990, and in the case of the latter, had reached their artistic heights. Even the deadest fucking genres like prog, traditional metal, and classic punk/hardcore still had strong torchbearers in that period of time.

And I'll even say the grunge explosion 91 gave us some pretty good records, although rock had yet to embrace the big stinky torrent of shit that the grunge scene had wound up unleashing.

posts.com: If, on the other hand, we estimate the worth of the Beautiful Arts by the culture they supply to the mind, and take as a standard the expansion of the faculties which must concur in the Judgement for cognition, Music will have the lowest place among them (as it has perhaps the highest among those arts which are valued for their pleasantness), because it merely plays with sensations. The formative arts are far before it in this point of view; for in putting the Imagination in a free play, which is also accordant with the Understanding, they at the same time carry on a serious business. This they do by producing a product that serves for concepts as a permanent self-commendatory vehicle for promoting their union with sensibility and thus, as it were, the urbanity of the higher cognitive powers. These two species of art take quite different courses; the first proceeds from sensations to indeterminate Ideas, the second from determinate Ideas to sensations. The latter produce permanent, the former only transitory impressions. The Imagination can recall the one and entertain itself pleasantly therewith; but the other either vanish entirely, or if they are recalled involuntarily by the Imagination they are rather wearisome than pleasant. Besides, there attaches to Music a certain want of urbanity from the fact that, chiefly from the character of its instruments, it extends its influence further than is desired (in the neighbourhood), and so as it were obtrudes itself, and does violence to the freedom of others who are not of the musical company. The Arts which appeal to the eyes do not do this; for we need only turn our eyes away, if we wish to avoid being impressed. The case of music is almost like that of the delight derived from a smell that diffuses itself widely. The man who pulls his perfumed handkerchief out of his pocket attracts the attention of all round him, even against their will, and he forces them, if they are to breathe at all, to enjoy the scent;

>>114109889
I wouldn't necessarily call Toscanini and Furtwangler friends. And they had one big thing in common when it came to Wagner: they were both slow. Strange to think it when Toscanini's reputation as a "fast" conductor precedes him, but his performances at Bayreuth were slower than the historic tradition there. Richard Strauss wasn't happy with either of them.
>>114111683
Toscanini was a very variable conductor like any one else. It's important to realize that we only really know him for the end of his career - that is with the NBC Orchestra and those late 30s-early 50s recordings. He was more critically acclaimed for his tenure with the New York Philharmonic, of which we have far fewer recordings (and the few that we do have are in pretty bad sound). The recordings that are in listenable shape reveal a more flexible conductor, especially outside of classical-era repertoire.

Fortepianos are a rather primitive version of the pianos we have today. >>114166081
Well to be fair its my first time blasting it so I can only give my first impressions, which isn't very useful for complex tech death stuff since you usually need a few blasts just to make sense of it. This one is pretty darn intense overall and high in the choas which is its main draw to me, there is also a number of breakdowns if you like those (I don't really). Speaking of breakdowns, it feels like a slight bit of punk is in the record, mostly its easy to hear in the vocals. Its not a stupid record though even if I just made it sound like it is, thats just the easy surface level stuff to see. The drumming on this album is pretty nuts, although I think thats basically mandatory for tech death disso bands.

If you aren't into dissoshit or noise related stuff, then this will probably be kick in the ballsack for you with how choatic it will sound, but for me its nothing too out there. The other reviewers act like this is some especially inaccessible, but personally I don't think so. Once you kind of break that instial disso reaction, most other disso bands become listanable.

>what to look for in the genre
For me its managing to sound choatic, evil, and outright mentally unstable; but also having a musical beauty to it. Yes its ripping your head off, but beneath the vicious riffs, the angular guitars, and the schzophrenic drumming; there is also a composition that shines ever most brightly with each listening. Ad Nauseam and DSO perfect this aspect to me. Pyrrhon is to me probably too focused on being "choatic" - which is its draw, but to me from my shallow listening of it (doing my second blast now) that same aspect kind of prevents it from materializing the ultimate refinement and artistry. Time will tell if maybe I'm just not catching the threads they have within the music, but this record is more is a Gorguts Obscura style riff by riff focused album with less interconnection in my opinion.

>sounds math to me
I can certainly see that and I know its what everyone else says too, but the album literally has the death metal package instrumentally. Certainly its always easy to call any disso with punk vocals to be mathy, and the album for sure has its mathish moments, but it is true death metal in its heart. The math aspects are however why I'll probably never see it as a truely great release, simply because I don't think mathcore is ever capable of true artistry since its always held back by its simplistic punk nature (even if mathcore is a giant leap above the usual punk garbage).

> I don't think anyone really craves the disso stuff
Once you get into it, I think you kind of do. If you are looking for the intensity and choatic feeling of what deathmetal was always about, but just much smarter and more advanced, then you aren't going to fit it elsewhere. I actually think dissoshit is just the logical conclusion of what pure "metal" was suppose to be, its evil, its choatic, its unpleasant, its virtuosic, its energetic, its inaccessible, and its going to be called a bunch of shitty noise by old men who don't get it.

>Suicide Euphoria by pissgrave
This is pretty cool actually, I had always dismissed this album/band as being some awful brutal or grind meme based on the name and art. The only problem with it is that while its sonically choatic, its still normal death metal underneath it. Musically its not living up to what it wants to be, and thats why dissoshit is so great to me!

>>114102256
>best amp sim for guitar and/or bass? maybe i'm just retarded but i can't get a good tone out of logic's default ones.
I have used Logic's amps and I found that for a hard rock/metal tone, I needed to do a couple of EQ moves. I think I did this.
1. High shelf boost before the amp.
2. Pretty big mid-scoop after the amp.
3. Pretty big bass boost around 70-100hz, depending on your tuning.
4. High-cut the really bright frequencies, at least above 10k, but possibly even lower than that.
5. You might want a boost around 6k for brightness.
6. Precise notch cuts to dampen resonant frequencies.

Remember that amp sims are really just algorithmic distortion and filters in a box. You can usually get a good tone out of anything with conscious EQ moves.

>>114125247
I remember the built-in tutorials being decent in 2012. They're probably at least as good now. Sorry I don't have more current info, but here are some very important hotkeys for starters:

>"Tab" switches between horizontal (arrangement) and vertical (session) views
>"Tab" + "Shift" switches between effects view on the bottom and edit view for the selected clip

Also, you'll want to download/install ASIO4ALL if you're on a PC, then set it as your audio driver in the settings menu. It'll help get you lower latency than default Windows drivers.

Last thing - learn where the "record arm" buttons are if you wanna record stuff. In the vertical view, you can click the little record circles for each clip space. If you wanna record to the main timeline, press F9 or click the record button up top. Good luck anon

posts.com:
>>114146088
Are you using an HDD or SSD? Do you have a separate drive for installing programs? My laptop could never run larger kontakt instruments, specifically drumlab, but now I have a desktop where the OS is on an m.2 drive, apps on an SSD, and recording/re-writable data on an HDD. Projects utilizing Kontakt instruments still increase the amount of time it takes to open a project, but it works.

Also, quick tip for everybody: if you only have one drive in your production machine, it should be an SSD. Whether you have a laptop, or a desktop, get an SSD. If you try to play live with an HDD, standing waves will destroy your system over time and cause glitches while you're on stage. And if you're running a laptop with only one drive, and you're trying to render/write audio while you're also reading audio from a kontakt instrument, you're gonna have a bad time. Any plugin that involves a sample library larger than 1GB is probably gonna make your computer scream if you're on a budget system.

Depends on the connection. An internal pcie drive will always be the fastest, so it's optimal for streaming, which makes it best for playing/midi playback for large sample library instruments. Thunderbolt is also really fast. But if you're using USB, that might slow it down to where you get skips in your playback. Depending on just how much latency the USB causes, you might get something that's only a minor issue that's tolerable while producing, but unacceptable for a live show.

>>114155164
You can use Reaper, it's Free in the same way that WinRAR is free, it will give you a polite message when you load it but is utterly unable to stop you from using it other than a guilt trip.
You can easily program simple drums with a mouse, but it's not that tactile and your beats will sound robotic. I would strongly strongly recommend a midi keyboard for controlling synths/keys, I thought I could get by without one, but you really can't. It makes your music so much fucking better it's unreal.
If you have guitars you will need an audio interface like a FocusRite one or M-Track. Then you should download some amp sims unless you want to get a mic and directly record your guitar amp which is fine but a bit of a bitch
The important thing to learn though is that a DAW won't help you create music, you need to have lots of music pre-made in your head or just waiting to burst out of you, and a DAW is basically just a camera that exists to snapshot the stuff you want to create

>>114163880
The thing that would most benefit you at this stage would probably be to get Vital and Serum, legally or otherwise, then watch a whole bunch of youtube videos of people making sounds in those synths. There are a bunch of other synths that are peers to those two, but those are the most common because one is so capable and well-established, and the other is free and equally capable. After you've done this enough times, you will start to understand how synths work, which will help you design good sounds from scratch.

>>114167709
Get used to that. If you're anything like me, that's just how it's gonna be for the first two or three years. Of course, all that can be avoided if you get to a strong level of competence in either mixing or composing right away. Great mixing can take a dull, uninspired track, and make it sound "professional" to normies, which might get them to give you a few more listens. Great songwriting and singing makes your mixing and mastering irrelevant for the most part. But if you have not gotten to a super high level of at least one of those skills, nothing you make will ever pass the you test, much less the normie test. You could be upper mid on songwriting, singing, mixing, and mastering, and it will effectively be the same to normies as your current music is to you. Just take one and drill it as deep as you can go. Then, once established, start hammering away at the other.

The end result of this will be door-opening music. The music itself won't do anything for you and will probably never even be discovered. But it will open the door for you to promote yourself to getting into live sets, studio collaboration, and Spotify playlists with bigger acts.
